						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">WedNESday wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">NMI always have the priority on IRQs. Even if a IRQ would be fired first, the NMI would come just after it, interupting it.</div><br /><br />And the reverse?</div>
<br />
<br />IRQ followed by NMI within the same instruction (but at least 2 cycles before the next instruction is fetched) results in NMI. NMI followed by IRQ <strong>still</strong> results in NMI.
<br />
<br />If you got IRQ in one instruction and then NMI in another, you'd leap straight from the IRQ handler into the NMI handler. If the reverse happened, the IRQ wouldn't be serviced, what with the 'I' flag having been set already.</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Quietust, QMT Productions
<br />P.S. If you don't get this note, let me know and I'll write you another.</div>
					<br clear="all" /><br />

